## Building an Angular Toggle Switch with Controlled State

**Mental Model:** The core idea is to create a reusable `ToggleSwitch` component that receives its `on` state as an `@Input()` and emits an `(onToggle)` event when its internal state changes. The parent component then listens to this event and updates the `on` input, thus controlling the toggle's state from the outside.

### Step 1 — Create the ToggleSwitch Component Structure
Define a simple component with an input for its `on` state and an output for when it's toggled. The template will include a visual representation of the switch and a click handler.

```typescript
import { Component, Input, Output, EventEmitter } from '@angular/core';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-toggle-switch',
  template: `
    <div
      class="toggle-switch"
      [style.background-color]="on ? '#4CAF50' : '#ccc'"
      (click)="toggle()"
    >
      <div
        class="slider"
        [style.transform]="on ? 'translateX(26px)' : 'translateX(0)'"
      ></div>
    </div>
  `,
  styles: [`
    .toggle-switch {
      position: relative;
      width: 50px;
      height: 24px;
      background-color: #ccc;
      border-radius: 24px;
      cursor: pointer;
      transition: background-color 0.3s;
      display: inline-block;
    }
    .slider {
      position: absolute;
      width: 22px;
      height: 22px;
      border-radius: 50%;
      background-color: white;
      top: 1px;
      left: 1px;
      transition: transform 0.3s;
    }
  `]
})
export class ToggleSwitchComponent {
  @Input() on: boolean = false;
  @Output() onToggle = new EventEmitter<boolean>();

  toggle(): void {
    this.onToggle.emit(!this.on);
  }
}
```

### Step 2 — Integrate into AppModule
Declare the `ToggleSwitchComponent` in your `AppModule` so that `AppComponent` can use it. This makes the component available within the application's scope.

```typescript
import { NgModule } from '@angular/core';
import { BrowserModule } from '@angular/platform-browser';
import { AppComponent } from './app.component';
import { ToggleSwitchComponent } from './toggle-switch.component'; // Import the new component

@NgModule({
  declarations: [
    AppComponent,
    ToggleSwitchComponent // Declare it here
  ],
  imports: [
    BrowserModule
  ],
  providers: [],
  bootstrap: [AppComponent]
})
export class AppModule { }
```

### Step 3 — Implement Controlled State in AppComponent
In the parent `AppComponent`, maintain a state variable that will be passed to the `ToggleSwitchComponent` via an input binding. Update this state variable when the `(onToggle)` event is emitted.

```typescript
import { Component } from '@angular/core';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-root',
  template: `
    <div style="padding: 20px;">
      <h1>Toggle Switch Demo</h1>
      <div *ngFor="let toggle of toggles; let i = index" style="margin-bottom: 15px;">
        <label style="margin-right: 10px;">Toggle {{ i + 1 }}:</label>
        <app-toggle-switch
          [on]="toggle.isOn"
          (onToggle)="handleToggle(i, $event)"
        ></app-toggle-switch>
        <span style="margin-left: 10px;">{{ toggle.isOn ? 'ON' : 'OFF' }}</span>
      </div>
      <button (click)="resetToggles()" style="margin-top: 20px; padding: 8px 15px; cursor: pointer;">Reset All</button>
    </div>
  `,
  styles: []
})
export class AppComponent {
  toggles: { isOn: boolean }[] = [
    { isOn: false },
    { isOn: true },
    { isOn: false }
  ];

  handleToggle(index: number, newState: boolean): void {
    if (index >= 0 && index < this.toggles.length) {
      this.toggles[index].isOn = newState;
    }
  }

  resetToggles(): void {
    this.toggles = [
      { isOn: false },
      { isOn: true },
      { isOn: false }
    ];
  }
}
```

### Step 4 — Create the ToggleSwitch Component File
Separate the `ToggleSwitchComponent` into its own file for better organization. This is standard practice for reusable components.

```typescript
// src/app/toggle-switch.component.ts
import { Component, Input, Output, EventEmitter } from '@angular/core';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-toggle-switch',
  template: `
    <div
      class="toggle-switch"
      [style.background-color]="on ? '#4CAF50' : '#ccc'"
      (click)="toggle()"
    >
      <div
        class="slider"
        [style.transform]="on ? 'translateX(26px)' : 'translateX(0)'"
      ></div>
    </div>
  `,
  styles: [`
    .toggle-switch {
      position: relative;
      width: 50px;
      height: 24px;
      background-color: #ccc;
      border-radius: 24px;
      cursor: pointer;
      transition: background-color 0.3s;
      display: inline-block;
    }
    .slider {
      position: absolute;
      width: 22px;
      height: 22px;
      border-radius: 50%;
      background-color: white;
      top: 1px;
      left: 1px;
      transition: transform 0.3s;
    }
  `]
})
export class ToggleSwitchComponent {
  @Input() on: boolean = false;
  @Output() onToggle = new EventEmitter<boolean>();

  toggle(): void {
    this.onToggle.emit(!this.on);
  }
}
```

**Edge Cases:**

| Scenario         | Handling                                                                  |
| :--------------- | :------------------------------------------------------------------------ |
| Disabled State   | Add an `@Input() disabled: boolean` and apply `[style.pointer-events]="disabled ? 'none' : 'auto'"` and `[style.opacity]="disabled ? '0.6' : '1'"` to the switch div. |
| Initial `on` value | Handled by `@Input() on: boolean = false;` providing a default.           |
| Accessibility    | Add `role="switch"`, `[attr.aria-checked]="on"` to the switch div.      |

**Interview tip:** Emphasize the separation of concerns: the `ToggleSwitchComponent` is stateless regarding its `on` property (it just reflects the input and emits changes), while the parent `AppComponent` manages the actual state.

